Location – SR 5/Biscayne Boulevard at NE 213 Street
C. H. Perez & Associates Consulting Engineers, Inc (P&A) was retained by the Florida
Department of Transportation (FDOT) District Six Office to perform a Safety Study at the
intersection of SR 5/Biscayne Boulevard and NE 213
study intersection was recommended for further study based on the findings presented in
the 2008 FDOT Top 5% High Crash List-Segments – Preliminary Safety Review completed
by the Department in September 2010. The previous study effort determined a pattern of
head-on, angle, and left-turn crashes at the study intersection based on the crash study
period of 2006 through 2008. These patterns were identified solely based on a review of
the crash data. This current study effort includes the development of collision diagrams
based on a review of all police reports. Therefore, there is the possibility that additional
crash patterns are identified or that the previous patterns are changed.
The objective of this study is to develop improvements and perform benefit/cost analysis
to identify suitable and cost effective improvements. These actions are intended to
mitigate the identified crash patterns and their associated probable causes. We have
developed and sketched the improvements to clearly identify the modifications required.
In addition, crash benefits, operational benefits, and construction costs associated with
the improvements have been quantified in a benefit/cost analysis. This ensures cost
effective improvements. The Department’s Electronic Review Comments (ERC) on the
submittal of the draft Safety Study report and P&A responses to the comments are
included in Appendix A. Finally, these efforts have been documented and presented in a
This report follows the procedures outlined in the Department’s Manual on Uniform Traffic
Studies (MUTS), the Highway Capacity Manual – 2000 Update (2000HCM), the Manual on
Uniform Traffic Control Devices (MUTCD), and the Highway Safety Improvements Program
Guidelines (HSIPG). This report will evaluate the following for the study location:
Figure 1 on the next page, shows the project area.
The study location is a signalized three leg intersection (“T” intersection) with exclusive
left-turn lanes on the southbound and westbound approaches. SR 5/Biscayne Boulevard is
a six-lane urban principal arterial divided by a raised median with a posted speed limit of
45 MPH. According to the Florida Department of Transportation (FDOT) Traffic Information
DVD (Year 2009), the Average Annual Daily Traffic (AADT) along SR 5/Biscayne Boulevard
is 52,000 vehicles per day (vpd), north of SR 5/Biscayne Boulevard (site located 200 ft
south of Miami-Dade/Broward County Line). The daily truck percentage for SR 5/Biscayne
Boulevard in 2009 was 2.61%, south of Miami-Dade/Broward County Line.
NE 213 Street is a four-lane divided facility that provides access to residential
communities located east of Biscayne Boulevard. The posted speed limit is 35 MPH within
the study limits. The closest signalized intersection to the study location is at SR
5/Biscayne Boulevard and NE 209 Street, which is located approximately 1,550 ft south of
The intersection is delineated by vacant land (part of the Gulfstream Park) on the
northeast corner, a restaurant and retail stores on the southeast corner, and a storage
warehouse and vacant land on the west side of the intersection. There are far side bus
stops located along northbound and southbound SR 5/Biscayne Boulevard. The approach

The signal phasing includes protected/permissive phasing for the southbound left-turn
movement, protected only for westbound movements and right-turn overlaps for
northbound and westbound approaches. Vehicles are not allowed to perform U-turn
movements at the northbound and southbound approaches; however, vehicles are
allowed to turn right on red at the northbound approach and from the right lane only at
the westbound approach. There are pedestrian crosswalks, push-buttons (to cross SR
5/Biscayne Boulevard), and pedestrian signal heads (without countdown display) provided
on the north and east legs of the intersection. There is on-street lighting along both sides
of SR 5/Biscayne Boulevard and ornamental street lighting along the median of NE 213

The study intersection is controlled via a mast arm traffic signal assembly. Regular
crosswalks are provided on the north and east legs of the intersection. There are
pedestrian signal heads without countdown display and pedestrian detectors to assist the
crossings. The traffic signal information for the intersection was obtained from the Miami-
Dade Traffic Signals & Signs Division database and is included in Appendix B. The
intersection operates under the following signal timing and phasing shown in Figure 3:
The data collection efforts for this study consisted of 72-hour Automatic Traffic Counts
(ATCs) and 6-hour Turning Movement Counts (TMCs) for the weekday period.
Based on the Automatic Traffic Counts collected (ATCs) (collected from February 8
through February 11, 2011), the one-hour morning, one-hour mid-day, and one-hour
afternoon peak traffic hours for the intersection during a typical weekday are from 8:15
AM to 9:15 AM, 12:15 AM to 1:15 PM, and from 5:00 PM to 6:00 PM, respectively. As
such, these intersection peak periods were selected for the turning movement count
periods. The TMCs were collected on Thursday, February 17, 2011. Pedestrian and truck
traffic volumes were also manually collected. The traffic count data and other volume
characteristics for the study intersection is summarized in Table 1. The data sheets can
be found in Appendix C. The traffic data was multiplied by the seasonal factor of 0.96
obtained from the 2009 Florida Traffic Information CD.

updating the database for crash information such as crash type, contributing cause,
vehicle travel direction, number of injuries, etc. The crash data [obtained from the
Department’s Crash Analysis Reporting System (CARS)] and police reports were provided
Given the geometric layout of this intersection (6 Lane x 4 Lane, Signalized, Turn Lanes,
3-Leg Divided Intersection), an Expected Value Analysis (EVA) was performed. The
abnormal crash types identified at the 95
bicycle (2) and fixed object (3). Similarly, the abnormal crash types identified at the 90
percentile were sideswipe (12) and backed into (2). Due to the low frequency of fixed
object and backed into crashes, these crash types will not be further investigated. Overall,
there were a total of 81 crashes in the three-year study period (06-08) with a yearly
breakdown of 19, 39, and 23 crashes for each year of analysis [respectively 2006, 2007,
and 2008]. There were 21 (25.9%) and 6 (7.4%) crashes which occurred during nighttime
and wet pavement surface conditions, respectively. Nighttime crashes are slightly above
the Districtwide average of 25% and wet pavement crashes are below the Districtwide
average of 30%. Overall, total crashes noticeably increased between 2006 and 2007, to
The three crash types with the greatest frequency within the three-year study period are
rear-end (36), left-turn (20), and sideswipe (12). Twenty out of the 36 rear-end crashes
occurred in the northbound direction and the review of hardcopy police reports indicates
that rear-end crashes were mostly related to traffic congestion (stop and going conditions)
and careless driving. Nineteen of the 20 left-turn crashes involved southbound left-turn
and northbound through vehicles. Based on the review of the hardcopy police reports, the
majority (14) of the left-turn crashes were caused by 1) southbound left-turn vehicles
failing to yield the right-of-way of northbound through vehicles, 2) sight distance
obstructions caused by other left-turning vehicles, and 3) misjudgment of available gaps.
Seven of the 12 sideswipe crashes occurred in the northbound direction. The review of the
police reports revealed that most of the sideswipe crashes occurred due to improper lane
Special consideration was given to collisions with pedestrians/bicyclists and nighttime
crashes. Review of hard copy police reports indicates that pedestrian/bicyclist crashes
were mostly attributed to careless driving and vehicles failing to yield to pedestrians in the
crosswalk. A further review of the nighttime crashes revealed that the majority of the
nighttime crashes were rear-end and left-turn collisions. Furthermore, most of these
crashes occurred in the north/south direction.

The following conceptual roadway improvements were evaluated based on the operational
and crash history of the intersection under study. Rear-end, left-turn, and sideswipe are
the three crash types to be targeted for mitigation. Also, special consideration will also be
given to collision with pedestrians/bicyclist and nighttime crashes. While evaluating the
following improvements, consideration was given as to whether any improvements would
be physically and economically feasible. The improvements have been detailed and
graphically depicted in Figure 4. The proposed improvements are as follows:
 Provide an additional southbound left-turn bay (dual left-turn – SBLT protected only
phasing). This improvement is proposed to relieve traffic congestion and reduce
aggressive maneuvers caused by the lack of capacity of the existing left-turn bay. The
recommendation of the additional southbound left-turn bay is supported by the
 A protected/permissive left-turn phase is currently in use. However, a total of 19
left-turn crashes involving northbound through and southbound left-turn
vehicles have been reported in the three-year analysis period (2006-2008).
 Vehicles performing southbound left-turns need to cross three lanes of opposing
through traffic to complete the turning maneuver. Note that traffic congestion
and the 45 mph speed of the opposing traffic do not facilitate finding appropriate
gaps to perform a safe left-turn during the permissive portion of the left-turn
 Collected traffic counts indicate a high demand of southbound left-turns (AM:
396, Midday: 437, and PM: 563). Furthermore, the City of Aventura
Comprehensive Plan indicates that a park is proposed on the northeast corner of
the intersection. Therefore, it is expected a higher demand of southbound left-
turns due to the planned future land use.
It should be noted that the implementation of this improvement will require shifting
the existing raised median to the east to accommodate the additional left-turn bay
and replacing the mast arms facing the northbound and southbound approaches. This
improvement requires an amount of additional right-of-way on the NE corner of the
intersection of SR 5/Biscayne Boulevard and NE 213 Street. Since, additional right-of-
way is required, coordination with the Gulfstream Park Racing Association, Inc., who
owns the currently vacant parcel located on the northeast corner, would be necessary
to obtain the right-of-way for this improvement. The amount of right-of-way needed
for the implementation of this improvement is approximately 3,420 square-feet. A
figure depicting the location of the approximate amount of right-of-way required is
In addition, the implementation of this proposed improvement will slightly increase
the crossing distance for pedestrians. Therefore, additional pedestrian green time
shall be provided to cross the north and west legs of the intersection. Note that the
duration of the proposed vehicular green phases, as depicted under section 2.7 of this
report, is long enough to allow increasing the pedestrian green time.
 Target: Left-turn, sideswipe, and rear-end crashes.
 Signal Optimization. This improvement is recommended to provide additional green
time to critical movements and avoid queues spilling back from left-turn bays into
 Install back-plates with retro-reflective tape border for all north/south signal heads to
enhance the contrast between the traffic signal indications and their surroundings for
 Refurbish westbound pavement markings. This improvement is intended to enhance
the lane designation of the westbound approach.
 Target: Sideswipe crashes in the westbound direction.

Based on the safety and operational deficiencies identified by the study for the
intersection of SR 5/Biscayne Boulevard at NE 213 Street and positive B/C results, the
improvements developed are recommended for implementation as stated below.
 Provide southbound dual left-turn - protected only phasing. This improvement
requires an amount of additional right-of-way on the NE corner of the intersection
of SR 5/Biscayne Boulevard and NE 213 Street. Coordination with the Gulfstream
Park Racing Association, Inc., who owns the currently vacant parcel located on the
northeast corner, would be necessary to obtain the right-of-way for this
 Signal timing optimization to provide additional green time to critical movements
and avoid queues pilling back from left-turn bays into adjacent through lanes.
